Raw dev notes -- A Week of Tinkering: AI, Alerts, and Code Cleanup

**1. Project Background:**
This past week was a whirlwind of jumping between a few personal projects. They're all about making my digital life a bit smoother, whether it's understanding how AI tools work under the hood, keeping tabs on my personal finances, or just making sure my home server doesn't silently die on me. It's my personal sandbox for learning new tech and solving my own little annoyances.

**2. What was done:**
Kicked off a couple of new AI-related explorations. I started digging into a popular AI Chrome extension, essentially importing its reference code to see how it ticks. This is tied into a broader "Claude config" project where I'm building out a baseline for managing settings, hooks, agents, and a plugin registry for interacting with various AI models. It's all about having a centralized way to control my AI interactions. I also tightened up the gitignore on that project to a strict whitelist, which felt like a good security move, even if it's a bit more work initially.

On the more practical side, I spent some time polishing up the "MyBill Dashboard." This involved implementing multi-tenant configuration (which was a bit of a beast to get right), fixing some UX quirks, and adding a "capture tool" – mostly for quick data snapshots.

Then there was the QMS_RH_RAG project, which got a much-needed codebase reorganization. I did a "5S audit" on it, which basically means I tidied everything up, added a proper README (finally!), and started looking into on-premise translation capabilities for it. This project is all about leveraging RAG for better, more localized AI responses.

Finally, my "Personal Information Hub" got some critical love. I fixed the watchdog to re-alert every two hours if an issue persists and added verification for Pushover notifications – gotta make sure those alerts actually reach me! Crucially, I also suppressed alerts on Fridays and Saturdays because, honestly, some things can wait until Monday. The session monitor also got an upgrade, now escalating to a Docker restart if things go really sideways, and it'll dedup alerts so I don't get spammed.

**3. What was hard or surprising:**
The multi-tenant config on the MyBill Dashboard was a real head-scratcher. It's one thing to build something for yourself, but making it flexible enough for multiple "tenants" (even if they're just different contexts for *me*) adds a whole layer of complexity I hadn't fully appreciated. Getting the UX just right after that was also a challenge – it's easy to get lost in the backend logic and forget the user experience.

The strict gitignore whitelist was also a bit of a pain. It's good practice, but man, you forget how many little config files or temporary build artifacts you generate until you have to explicitly allow them. It felt like fighting my own tools for a bit.

And the Personal Information Hub fixes, while seemingly small, highlighted how much I rely on these background systems. Debugging why a Pushover alert *didn't* fire, or why a Docker container *didn't* restart, can be surprisingly frustrating. It's like trying to fix a ghost in the machine. The "suppress Fri/Sat" feature was a small win, but it took a bit of thought to implement robustly without missing critical alerts.

**4. Personal reflection:**
This week felt like a good mix of deep dives and broad strokes. I really enjoyed the initial exploration into the Claude extension – it's like being a digital detective, trying to piece together how something works from the outside in. It reminds me that even complex tools are just code, and you can always learn from them. The config project feels like a foundational step towards a more integrated AI workflow for myself, which is exciting.

On the other hand, wrestling with the dashboard's multi-tenancy and the monitoring fixes for the Information Hub felt more like maintenance, but crucial maintenance. It's a reminder that building is only half the battle; keeping things running smoothly and reliably is just as important, if not more so, for long-term sanity. It felt good to finally get those monitoring fixes in place, knowing I won't be woken up by a non-critical alert on a Saturday morning. It's about setting boundaries, even with my own code.

I'm learning to appreciate the "chore" commits more – the gitignores, the READMEs, the 5S audits. They're not glamorous, but they make future me's life so much easier. It's a sign of growth, I think, moving beyond just "making it work" to "making it maintainable."

**5. What's next:**
Continue building out the AI config system and integrate it with more tools.
